I found several recent research papers on activation probing and internal representations related to truthfulness in LLMs from 2025-2026. Here are the key findings:

## Recent Empirical Work on Truthfulness Probing

Research shows that value vectors within MLP modules support factual recall, and analysis reveals that certain value vectors exhibit consistent activation patterns when processing truthful versus untruthful contents—either increasing or decreasing in activation magnitude. These value vectors are most prominent in the middle and final layers of the model.

## Probe Generalization Challenges

A significant recent finding is that trained probes for statement truthfulness fail to generalize across datasets and tasks, and particularly across different domains. Levinstein and Herrmann (2025) find that non-linear truthfulness probes fail to generalize to even negated variants of their training data.

## Steering and Intervention

Research has shown that activations can be steered for truthfulness. Additionally, linear probing reveals that certain concepts such as honesty, harmlessness, and fairness emerge as linearly separable directions in LLM activation spaces.

## Knowledge Representation Brittleness

A 2025 paper titled "LLM Knowledge is Brittle: Truthfulness Representations Rely on Superficial Resemblance" provides empirical evidence that truthfulness representations in LLMs may not be as robust as previously thought, with generalization issues across different contexts and datasets.


