## CoT Grading and Monitorability Research

OpenAI found limited accidental CoT grading in some released models, fixed the affected reward pathways, and found no clear evidence that monitorability degraded. Although there is broad agreement that CoT should not be graded, this can still happen accidentally, and to mitigate this, OpenAI introduced an internal system to automatically detect cases where RL rewards were computed based on a model's CoT.

## Key Monitorability Findings

Monitorability generally improves as models produce longer CoTs, and monitors that can inspect CoT or all messages are substantially more informative than monitors limited to actions alone. Chain-of-thought monitorability is an important part of OpenAI's safety strategy because it allows them to oversee a model's reasoning to catch misbehavior, rather than relying only on actions or final responses.

## Open-Sourcing Efforts

In April 23, 2026, OpenAI released a subset of datasets and reference code from their chain-of-thought monitorability work, including most datasets from their monitorability evaluation suite, code for computing the monitorability metric g-mean2, and a new cross-fit filtering strategy.


