## EleutherAI's SAE Interpretability Research

EleutherAI has investigated different techniques for generating and scoring text explanations of SAE features, and released an open source library to allow people to do research on auto-interpreted features. Open source models generate and evaluate text explanations of SAE features reasonably well, albeit somewhat worse than closed models like Claude 3.5 Sonnet.

Code can be found at https://github.com/EleutherAI/sae-auto-interp. The EleutherAI blog post on this topic was published on July 30, 2024, and covers their work on automated interpretability for sparse autoencoder features.

The research also shows that automatically interpreting 1.5M features of GPT-2 with the current pipeline would cost $1300 in API calls to Llama 3.1 or $8500 with Claude 3.5 Sonnet.

Additionally, EleutherAI has contributed to research comparing SAEs with other approaches, with work on transcoders that show higher interpretability scores when compared to SAEs.


