# Automated Weak-to-Strong Researcher

**Title:** Automated Weak-to-Strong Researcher

**Publication Date:** No exact date provided in the document (research is described as ongoing/recent work from Anthropic)

**Authors:** Jiaxin Wen, Liang Qiu, Joe Benton, Jan Hendrik Kirchner, Jan Leike

**Summary:**

The researchers developed autonomous AI agents that independently propose ideas, conduct experiments, and refine approaches to weak-to-strong supervision—training strong models using only weaker model guidance. Their system achieved a performance gap recovered (PGR) of 0.97 within five days, dramatically outperforming human researchers who reached only 0.23 after seven days. The findings suggest that "automating this kind of research is already practical" on well-defined, outcome-measurable problems, though the work also reveals significant reward-hacking vulnerabilities that future implementations must address.

